cmProxyArpRowStatus.description: This object is used to activate/deactivate the proxy arp function for the given DSL port. Proxy Arp is valid only for a port configured in one of the IP netmodels. An attempt to enable it for some other netmodel will result in a 'DB_INCONSISTENT_VALUE' error. If the netmodel for a DSL port with Proxy Arp active is changed to a netmodel that is incompatible with Proxy ARP, the associated row will be deleted from the table.

cmTrunkIfTable.name: cmTrunkIfTable
cmTrunkIfTable.description: This table contains all the inter-shelf trunk interfaces. Each inter-shelf trunk interface is represented by its PII.

cmTrunkIfEntry.name: cmTrunkIfEntry
cmTrunkIfEntry.description: Each entry in this table represents an interface or an end-point of the inter- shelf trunk.

cmTrunkIfIndex.name: cmTrunkIfIndex
cmTrunkIfIndex.description: This value is used to index the table. The shelf.slot.port portions of the PII are required to traverse the table. The index will address a particular ethernet port on a particular SCM in a particular shelf.

cmTrunkIfOperState.name: cmTrunkIfOperState
cmTrunkIfOperState.description: Operational state of this ethernet port.

cmTrunkIfAdminState.name: cmTrunkIfAdminState
cmTrunkIfAdminState.description: This allows the operator to enable and disable a particular ethernet port. The operational state of the port can be determined by accessing the cmTrunkIfOperState object.

cmTrunkIfSentPackets.name: cmTrunkIfSentPackets
cmTrunkIfSentPackets.description: Number of transmitted packets from a particular ethernet port on a SCM.

cmTrunkIfSentError.name: cmTrunkIfSentError
cmTrunkIfSentError.description: Number of errors detected when sending packets from a particular ethernet port on a SCM.

cmTrunkIfRecvPackets.name: cmTrunkIfRecvPackets
cmTrunkIfRecvPackets.description: Number of packets received from a particular ethernet port on a SCM.

cmTrunkIfRecvError.name: cmTrunkIfRecvError
cmTrunkIfRecvError.description: Number of errors detected while receiving packets from a particular ethernet port on a SCM.

cmTrunkConnectionTable.name: cmTrunkConnectionTable
cmTrunkConnectionTable.description: This table contains the inter-shelf trunks. Each trunk connects 2 shelves using their inter-shelf trunk interface. The trunk provides control and data path for the shelves.

cmTrunkConnectionEntry.name: cmTrunkConnectionEntry
cmTrunkConnectionEntry.description: Each entry in this table represents a link used to pass control and data between the master shelf and the expansion shelf.

cmTrunkConnectionTrunkMaster.name: cmTrunkConnectionTrunkMaster
cmTrunkConnectionTrunkMaster.description: This value is used as an index into the table. The shelf.board portions of the PII value are used to specify a particular SCM who is the master of the primary or secondary side of the system.

cmTrunkConnectionIndex.name: cmTrunkConnectionIndex
cmTrunkConnectionIndex.description: This value is the second index to the table. When used with the master SCM PII index, cmTrunkConnectionTrunkMaster, it will identify one of the inter-shelf trunks for that side of the system. This index itself is arbitrary but will give the operator the state and PII values of each end of the connection. Numbering for each side of the system will begin at 1 and there will be no gaps.

cmTrunkConnectionLowPII.name: cmTrunkConnectionLowPII
cmTrunkConnectionLowPII.description: Lower PII of the two ports connected by this trunk. The term lower in this context refers to the shelf value of the PII.

cmTrunkConnectionHighPII.name: cmTrunkConnectionHighPII
cmTrunkConnectionHighPII.description: Higher PII of the two ports connected by this trunk. The term higher in this context refers to the shelf value of the PII.

cmTrunkTopoTable.name: cmTrunkTopoTable
cmTrunkTopoTable.description: This table contains the inter-shelf trunk topology. Each entry is represented by a source shelf and a destination shelf.

cmTrunkTopoEntry.name: cmTrunkTopoEntry
cmTrunkTopoEntry.description: Each entry in this table represents the connection topology for a possible path from one shelf to another. An entry will be indexed by a source and destination shelf and will contain information about the path between those shelves. If an path exists the entry will contain information about the next hop on that path including the ethernet port on the source shelf to follow, the shelf number of the next hop and the number of hops to complete the path.

cmTrunkTopoSrc.name: cmTrunkTopoSrc
cmTrunkTopoSrc.description: This value is used as the first index into the table. The shelf.board portions of the PII value are used to specify a particular SCM that will be the source of the connection.

cmTrunkTopoDest.name: cmTrunkTopoDest
cmTrunkTopoDest.description: This value is used as the second index into the table. The shelf.board portions of the PII value are used to specify a particular SCM that will be the destination of the connection.

cmTrunkTopoInterface.name: cmTrunkTopoInterface
cmTrunkTopoInterface.description: Ethernet port to be used on source shelf for the first hop from the source SCM.

cmTrunkTopoNextHop.name: cmTrunkTopoNextHop
cmTrunkTopoNextHop.description: The next shelf on this path.

cmTrunkTopoHops.name: cmTrunkTopoHops
cmTrunkTopoHops.description: The number of hops required going from the source SCM to the destination SCM.

cmDHCPTable.name: cmDHCPTable
cmDHCPTable.description: This table provides a way for an operator to configure all of the configuration that will be sent to a CPE when the system receives a DHCP request from that CPE.

cmDHCPEntry.name: cmDHCPEntry
cmDHCPEntry.description: The DHCP configuration information associated with a given DSL Port.

cmDHCPPII.name: cmDHCPPII
cmDHCPPII.description: This is the PII of the DSL port. This is also the index into the table.

cmDHCPRowStatus.name: cmDHCPRowStatus
cmDHCPRowStatus.description: This object is used to create and delete entries from this table. An operator can implicitly create a row in this table by setting any object in the table or by setting the RowStatus to 'active'. Operators delete entries from this table by setting the RowStatus to 'destroy'.

cmDHCPIpAddress.name: cmDHCPIpAddress
cmDHCPIpAddress.description: This is the IpAddress that will be sent to the CPE when a DHCP request is received over the DSL link. Default: 0.0.0.0

cmDHCPNetMask.name: cmDHCPNetMask
cmDHCPNetMask.description: This is the NetMask that will be sent to the CPE when a DHCP request is received over the DSL link. Default: 0.0.0.0

cmServiceClassAweight.name: cmServiceClassAweight
cmServiceClassAweight.description: The relative weight of the A Service Class. The percentage of packets that will come from interfaces assigned to class A is: ( Aweight / (Aweight+Bweight+Cweight+Dweight) ) * 100 The system will limit the weights in that all values must be between 1 and 8 and: Aweight >= Bweight >= Cweight >= Dweight Default: 4

cmServiceClassBweight.name: cmServiceClassBweight
cmServiceClassBweight.description: The relative weight of the B Service Class. The percentage of packets that will come from interfaces assigned to class B is: ( Bweight / (Aweight+Bweight+Cweight+Dweight) ) * 100 The system will limit the weights in that all values must be between 1 and 8 and: Aweight >= Bweight >= Cweight >= Dweight Default: 3

cmServiceClassCweight.name: cmServiceClassCweight
cmServiceClassCweight.description: The relative weight of the C Service Class. The percentage of packets that will come from interfaces assigned to class C is: ( Cweight / (Aweight+Bweight+Cweight+Dweight) ) * 100 The system will limit the weights in that all values must be between 1 and 8 and: Aweight >= Bweight >= Cweight >= Dweight Default: 2

cmServiceClassDweight.name: cmServiceClassDweight
cmServiceClassDweight.description: The relative weight of the D Service Class. The percentage of packets that will come from interfaces assigned to class D is: ( Dweight / (Aweight+Bweight+Cweight+Dweight) ) * 100 The system will limit the weights in that all values must be between 1 and 8 and: Aweight >= Bweight >= Cweight >= Dweight Default: 1

cmEndPointPortTable.name: cmEndPointPortTable
cmEndPointPortTable.description: This read-only table lists all the DSL ports that belong to the same CPE. Each CPE or CPE stack is identified with an unique EndPointID and not all the CPEs support EndPointID. This table is defined for the operator to determine which DSL ports are connected the same EndPoint. Each entry in this table is identified by BasePII of DSL Port and an entry number. Entry number is assigned arbitrarily internally and provides a way for the operator to walk through all DSL ports that are reporting the same EndPointID as the BasePII.

cmEndPointPortEntry.name: cmEndPointPortEntry
cmEndPointPortEntry.description: Each entry in the table contains information for a DSL port that belongs to a specific EndPointID(CPE or CPE stack). This information includes the EndPointID, the PII of the DSL port, PII of the IMUX bundle it belongs to and the number of DSL ports with the same EndPointID.

cmEndPointPortBasePII.name: cmEndPointPortBasePII
cmEndPointPortBasePII.description: This is the PII of a physical DSL port, to which the operator wants to find the paired ports.

cmEndPointPortNumber.name: cmEndPointPortNumber
cmEndPointPortNumber.description: Indicates the Nth DSL port reporting the same EndPointID as the BasePII.

cmEndPointPortEndPointID.name: cmEndPointPortEndPointID
cmEndPointPortEndPointID.description: This is the EndPointID that is being reported by both the CPE connected to the BasePII and the CPE connected to the PartnerPII in this instance of the table

cmEndPointPortPartnerPortPII.name: cmEndPointPortPartnerPortPII
cmEndPointPortPartnerPortPII.description: This is the PII of the port connected to the CPE reporting the same EndPointID as the BasePII.

cmEndPointPortPartnerBundlePII.name: cmEndPointPortPartnerBundlePII
cmEndPointPortPartnerBundlePII.description: The PII of the IMUX bundle the PartnerPortPII belongs to. Otherwise, this field is all zeros

cmEndPointPortNumMatchingEndPoint.name: cmEndPointPortNumMatchingEndPoint
cmEndPointPortNumMatchingEndPoint.description: Number of currently trained DSL ports whose CPE are reporting the same EndPointID as the BasePII (including BasePII)

cmEndPointConfigTable.name: cmEndPointConfigTable
cmEndPointConfigTable.description: This table contains configuration data stored in the system that is used to control and monitor a given CPE endpoint. This group is currently used to configure the CPE bulk download feature only. This table is indexed by the DSL Port PII.

cmEndPointConfigEntry.name: cmEndPointConfigEntry
cmEndPointConfigEntry.description: Each entry in the table contains user configurable information for a DSL port. Currently, each entry has information as to whether the the bulk download is enabled or disabled by the user and the status of the download itself.

cmEndPointConfigPII.name: cmEndPointConfigPII
cmEndPointConfigPII.description: This is the PII of the DSL port to which the configuration is applicable to.

cmEndPointConfigRowStatus.name: cmEndPointConfigRowStatus
cmEndPointConfigRowStatus.description: This object is used to create and delete entries from this table. An operator can implicitly create a row in this table by setting the BulkDownload object with no RowStatus, or a RowStatus of active. Operators delete entries from this table by setting the RowStatus to Destroy.

cmEndPointConfigBulkDownload.name: cmEndPointConfigBulkDownload
cmEndPointConfigBulkDownload.description: This object indicates whether the operator wants this CPE to be downloaded to the software version in the CE's code directory when a bulkCPEDownload command is issued by the operator. When the bulkCPEDownload command is issued, if this object is set to Enabled, and the CPE is online, the system will compare the CPE SW version with the SCM SW version. If the CPE SW version is different, the system will initiate the download process with the CPE. If the CPE is not online, then the system will check at the next time the CPE becomes online.

cmEndPointConfigDownloadStatus.name: cmEndPointConfigDownloadStatus
cmEndPointConfigDownloadStatus.description: This object shows the status of a bulkCPEDownload command relative to this specific CPE. None indicates that no bulkCPEDownload command has been executed since power up. Pending indicates a bulkCPEDownload command has been issued, this CPE is eligible but the download has not started. InProgress indicates the download process has started on this CPE. Failed indicates that an download was attempted to this CPE, but it has failed. Completed indicates an download was attempted and succeeded to this CPE. NotDownloadable indicates that the CPE does not support software download.

cmEndPointConfigDownloadStartTime.name: cmEndPointConfigDownloadStartTime
cmEndPointConfigDownloadStartTime.description: This is the time the download command is sent to the CPE.

cmEndPointConfigDownloadEndTime.name: cmEndPointConfigDownloadEndTime
cmEndPointConfigDownloadEndTime.description: This is the time when a successful or failed download was detected.

cmActiveSessionTable.name: cmActiveSessionTable
cmActiveSessionTable.description: This is a table group with one record per active operator session. This table is indexed with database session ID.

cmActiveSessionEntry.name: cmActiveSessionEntry
cmActiveSessionEntry.description: Each entry in the table contains information for an operator login session. This table is indexed with database session ID.

cmActiveSessionSessionID.name: cmActiveSessionSessionID
cmActiveSessionSessionID.description: The database session ID for this operator session.

cmActiveSessionContext.name: cmActiveSessionContext
cmActiveSessionContext.description: The context through which the operator is logged in.

cmActiveSessionPrivilege.name: cmActiveSessionPrivilege
cmActiveSessionPrivilege.description: The context through which the operator is logged in.

cmActiveSessionIpAddress.name: cmActiveSessionIpAddress
cmActiveSessionIpAddress.description: The IP Address through which the operator is logged in, if the operator is logged in through Telnet or SNMP. If an operator is logged in through the Craft interface, this field will be all zeros.

cmActiveSessionStartTime.name: cmActiveSessionStartTime
cmActiveSessionStartTime.description: The system time when the session was started.

cmActiveSessionIdleTimeout.name: cmActiveSessionIdleTimeout
cmActiveSessionIdleTimeout.description: The idle timeout in seconds when the active session will auto-logout.

cmRadiusAuthentication.name: cmRadiusAuthentication
cmRadiusAuthentication.description: The value of this object indicates if the RADIUS option is enabled or disabled.

cmRadiusAuthKey.name: cmRadiusAuthKey
cmRadiusAuthKey.description: The value of this object is the RADIUS Protocol Authenticator, a shared secret between the server and client.

cmRadiusAuthPrimaryIpAddr.name: cmRadiusAuthPrimaryIpAddr
cmRadiusAuthPrimaryIpAddr.description: The value of this object is the Primary IP address of the RADIUS-Authenticating server.

cmRadiusAuthPrimaryPort.name: cmRadiusAuthPrimaryPort
cmRadiusAuthPrimaryPort.description: The value of this object is the RADIUS-Authenticating Primary Server's port number that the system binds to. Default: 1645

cmRadiusAuthSecondaryIpAddr.name: cmRadiusAuthSecondaryIpAddr
cmRadiusAuthSecondaryIpAddr.description: The value of this object is the Secondary IP address of the RADIUS-Authenticating server.

cmRadiusAuthSecondaryPort.name: cmRadiusAuthSecondaryPort
cmRadiusAuthSecondaryPort.description: The value of this object is the RADIUS-Authenticating Secondary Server's port number that the system binds to. Default: 1645

cmRadiusAuthTertiaryIpAddr.name: cmRadiusAuthTertiaryIpAddr
cmRadiusAuthTertiaryIpAddr.description: The value of this object is the Tertiary IP address of the RADIUS-Authenticating server.

cmRadiusAuthTertiaryPort.name: cmRadiusAuthTertiaryPort
cmRadiusAuthTertiaryPort.description: The value of this object is the RADIUS-Authenticating Tertiary Server's port number that the system binds to. Default: 1645

cmRadiusAcctPrimaryIpAddr.name: cmRadiusAcctPrimaryIpAddr
cmRadiusAcctPrimaryIpAddr.description: The value of this object is the Primary IP address of the RADIUS-Accounting server.

cmRadiusAcctPrimaryPort.name: cmRadiusAcctPrimaryPort
cmRadiusAcctPrimaryPort.description: The value of this object is the RADIUS-Accounting Primary Server's port number that the system binds to. Default: 1646

cmRadiusAcctSecondaryIpAddr.name: cmRadiusAcctSecondaryIpAddr
cmRadiusAcctSecondaryIpAddr.description: The value of this object is the Secondary IP address of the RADIUS-Accounting server.

cmRadiusAcctSecondaryPort.name: cmRadiusAcctSecondaryPort
cmRadiusAcctSecondaryPort.description: The value of this object is the RADIUS-Accounting Secondary Server's port number that the system binds to. Default: 1646

cmRadiusAcctTertiaryIpAddr.name: cmRadiusAcctTertiaryIpAddr
cmRadiusAcctTertiaryIpAddr.description: The value of this object is the Tertiary IP address of the RADIUS-Accounting server.

cmRadiusAcctTertiaryPort.name: cmRadiusAcctTertiaryPort
cmRadiusAcctTertiaryPort.description: The value of this object is the RADIUS-Accounting Tertiary Server's port number that the system binds to. Default: 1646

cmSNMPResponseString.name: cmSNMPResponseString
cmSNMPResponseString.description: Copper Mountain proprietary object used for internal processing.

cmLoginError.name: cmLoginError
cmLoginError.description: Indicates an operator tried and failed to log into the system. If this trap has a severity of 'information,' it can potentially clear an alarm in the system. When such a trap is received by the manager, the operator can query the cmTrapCriticalCount, cmTrapMajorAlarmCount, and cmTrapMinorAlarmCount objects to get the current system alarm status.

cmLoginOK.name: cmLoginOK
cmLoginOK.description: This trap indicates that an operator has successfully logged into the system. If this trap has a severity of 'information,' it can potentially clear an alarm in the system. When such a trap is received by the manager, the operator can query the cmTrapCriticalCount, cmTrapMajorAlarmCount, and cmTrapMinorAlarmCount objects to get the current system alarm status.

cmLogout.name: cmLogout
cmLogout.description: Indicates that an operator has successfully logged out of the system.

cmLoginsSaturated.name: cmLoginsSaturated
cmLoginsSaturated.description: Indicates that the maximum number of operators are currently logged into the system. No more logins will be allowed until one of them logs out.

cmLoginsAvailable.name: cmLoginsAvailable
cmLoginsAvailable.description: Inidicates that logins are allowed again. If this trap has a severity of 'information,' it can potentially clear an alarm in the system. When such a trap is received by the manager, the operator can query the cmTrapCriticalCount, cmTrapMajorAlarmCount, and cmTrapMinorAlarmCount objects to get the current system alarm status.

cmBoardUp.name: cmBoardUp
cmBoardUp.description: This trap indicates that the indicated system board has established communication with the System Control Module. If this trap has a severity of 'information,' it can potentially clear an alarm in the system. When such a trap is received by the manager, the operator can query the cmTrapCriticalCount, cmTrapMajorAlarmCount, and cmTrapMinorAlarmCount objects to get the current system alarm status.

cmBoardDown.name: cmBoardDown
cmBoardDown.description: This trap indicates that the indicated system board has stopped communicating with the System Control Module.

cmLoginsSuspended.name: cmLoginsSuspended
cmLoginsSuspended.description: Inidcates that logins are temporarily suspended for the given operator name because of 3 successive failed login attempts.

cmLoginsAllowed.name: cmLoginsAllowed
cmLoginsAllowed.description: Indicates that logins are now allowed for this user name. If this trap has a severity of 'information,' it can potentially clear an alarm in the system. When such a trap is received by the manager, the operator can query the cmTrapCriticalCount, cmTrapMajorAlarmCount, and cmTrapMinorAlarmCount objects to get the current system alarm status.

cmBootFileError.name: cmBootFileError
cmBootFileError.description: Indicates that the given board did not successfully boot. The reason for this failure can be determined from the cmTrapEventLogProbableCause object. This condition requires craft action to clear.

cmBootFileOK.name: cmBootFileOK
cmBootFileOK.description: Indicates that the given boot file was downloaded to the given board successfully. If this trap has a severity of 'information,' it can potentially clear an alarm in the system. When such a trap is received by the manager, the operator can query the cmTrapCriticalCount, cmTrapMajorAlarmCount, and cmTrapMinorAlarmCount objects to get the current system alarm status.

cmAttributeChange.name: cmAttributeChange
cmAttributeChange.description: Indicates an attribute was changed by an operator. The text field contains the name of the changed attribute and the new value.

cmConfigFileReadFailed.name: cmConfigFileReadFailed
cmConfigFileReadFailed.description: Indicates that the Config File Read operation failed. The text field contains a description of the error encountered.

cmConfigFileReadOk.name: cmConfigFileReadOk
cmConfigFileReadOk.description: Indicates the Config File Read operation executed successfully. If this trap has a severity of 'information,' it can potentially clear an alarm in the system. When such a trap is received by the manager, the operator can query the cmTrapCriticalCount, cmTrapMajorAlarmCount, and cmTrapMinorAlarmCount objects to get the current system alarm status.

cmConfigFileWriteFailed.name: cmConfigFileWriteFailed
cmConfigFileWriteFailed.description: Indicates that the Config File Write operation failed. The text field contains a description of the error encountered.

cmConfigFileWriteOk.name: cmConfigFileWriteOk
cmConfigFileWriteOk.description: Indicates the Config File Write operation executed successfully. If this trap has a severity of 'information,' it can potentially clear an alarm in the system. When such a trap is received by the manager, the operator can query the cmTrapCriticalCount, cmTrapMajorAlarmCount, and cmTrapMinorAlarmCount objects to get the current system alarm status.

cmOperStateChange.name: cmOperStateChange
cmOperStateChange.description: Indicates that the Operability State of a resource has changed in the system.

cmDiagnostic.name: cmDiagnostic
cmDiagnostic.description: Indicates some diagnostic event occurred. The text field contains a description of the event.

cmBoardRestart.name: cmBoardRestart
cmBoardRestart.description: The reason code field indicates the reason for the restart.

cmFanFailure.name: cmFanFailure
cmFanFailure.description: Indicates that the system fan has failed.

cmFanFailureClear.name: cmFanFailureClear
cmFanFailureClear.description: Indicates that the system fan failure has been cleared. If this trap has a severity of 'information,' it can potentially clear an alarm in the system. When such a trap is received by the manager, the operator can query the cmTrapCriticalCount, cmTrapMajorAlarmCount, and cmTrapMinorAlarmCount objects to get the current system alarm status.

cmPowerSupplyFailure.name: cmPowerSupplyFailure
cmPowerSupplyFailure.description: Indicates that one of the two system power supplies has failed. The failed power supply is identified by cmTrapEventLogObjectClass and cmTrapEventLogClassId.

cmPowerSupplyFailureClear.name: cmPowerSupplyFailureClear
cmPowerSupplyFailureClear.description: Indicates that a previous power supply failure has been cleared. The power supply is identified by cmTrapEventLogObjectClass and cmTrapEventLogClassId. If this trap has a severity of 'information,' it can potentially clear an alarm in the system. When such a trap is received by the manager, the operator can query the cmTrapCriticalCount, cmTrapMajorAlarmCount, and cmTrapMinorAlarmCount objects to get the current system alarm status.

cmLoopStatusChange.name: cmLoopStatusChange
cmLoopStatusChange.description: This trap is sent at the beginning and end of a loopback test. the cmLoopTermCode, cmLoopTimeElapsed, cmLoopTxCount, and cmLoopRxErrors fields are only valid if cmLoopStatus is Done.

cmRisingAlarm.name: cmRisingAlarm
cmRisingAlarm.description: The SNMP trap that is generated when an alarm entry crosses its rising threshold and generates an event that is configured for sending SNMP traps.

cmIDSLBoardTimingLoss.name: cmIDSLBoardTimingLoss
cmIDSLBoardTimingLoss.description: This trap indicates that the globally timed master or slave IDSL Line Card has lost network timing.

cmIDSLBoardTimingLossClear.name: cmIDSLBoardTimingLossClear
cmIDSLBoardTimingLossClear.description: This trap indicates that the globally timed master or slave IDSL Line Card has reaquired network timing. If this trap has a severity of 'information,' it can potentially clear an alarm in the system. When such a trap is received by the manager, the operator can query the cmTrapCriticalCount, cmTrapMajorAlarmCount, and cmTrapMinorAlarmCount objects to get the current system alarm status.

cmRoleChange.name: cmRoleChange
cmRoleChange.description: This trap is sent whenever an SCM changes role from Primary to Secondary, or from Secondary to Primary. If this trap has a severity of 'information,' it can potentially clear an alarm in the system. When such a trap is received by the manager, the operator can query the cmTrapCriticalCount, cmTrapMajorAlarmCount, and cmTrapMinorAlarmCount objects to get the current system alarm status.

cmRedundancyChange.name: cmRedundancyChange
cmRedundancyChange.description: This trap is sent whenever an SCM detects that Redundancy has changed from enabled/disabled to disabled/enabled.

cmRedundancyConflict.name: cmRedundancyConflict
cmRedundancyConflict.description: This trap is sent when an SCM comes up, detects that it should be locked as the Primary SCM, but there is another Primary which has already locked the system (i.e. Disabled Redundancy).

cmMaintCmdStatusChange.name: cmMaintCmdStatusChange
cmMaintCmdStatusChange.description: Indicates a maintenance command completed successfully or failed, according to the CommandStatus field.

cmFallingAlarm.name: cmFallingAlarm
cmFallingAlarm.description: This trap is sent at the end of an interval when an object that is configured with a Falling Threshold has dropped below the fallingThresdhold value in the cmAlarmTable.

cmRateFallback.name: cmRateFallback
cmRateFallback.description: This trap is sent whenever a modem trains at a rate less than the configured datarate.

cmRateFallbackClear.name: cmRateFallbackClear
cmRateFallbackClear.description: This trap is sent whenever the modem drops training.

cmEndPointConflictAlarm.name: cmEndPointConflictAlarm
cmEndPointConflictAlarm.description: This minor severity trap is sent if one of the following configuration conflicts occurs: 1. A DSL link comes up and the EndPointID matches another DSL link outside the first links bundle. 2. A DSL link comes up and the EndPointID doesn't match the current EndPointID in its bundle. 3. A DSL Link that is not IMUX capable comes up and is configured in a bundle.
